{"version":"1.2","person":{"datePublished":"2023-10-29","name":"Sir John Wiltshire , M.P., of Arundel and Lyminster","nameForms":[{"lang":"en","fullText":"Sir John Wiltshire , M.P., of Arundel and Lyminster","parts":[{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Prefix","value":"Sir"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Given","value":"John"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Surname","value":"Wiltshire"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Suffix","value":", M.P., of Arundel and Lyminster"}],"order":"EUROTYPIC"}],"gender":"Male","lifespan":"1410–1454","fullLifespan":"after March 1410–1454","birthDate":"+1410-03","birthPlace":{"address":"Hellesdon, Norfolk, England","geo":{"latitude":52.63333,"longitude":1.25,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"deathDate":"+1454","deathPlace":{"address":"Arundel, Sussex, England","geo":{"latitude":50.854,"longitude":-0.5577,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"userCertifiedLifeSummary":"Sir John Wiltshire was born after 1409 in Hellesdon, Norfolk, England. The timing of his father's marriage to his second wife, Alice Heylesdon, and John's estimated birth is based on the death of Alice's previous husband, John Gurney, who died on 4 Dec 1408, and was \"followed by their 10-year-old son Edmund shortly after.\" Additionally his father's first wife Blanche de Mowbray died on 21 July 1409. Therefore Sir John Wiltshire is born at minimum +9 months after this date. \n\nThe History of Parliament site confuses facts between this John Wiltshire and his father, Sir John Wiltshire, Knt., of Arundel, who is noted from my research as the retainer of the Earl of Arundel, served as a Tax Collector, Mayor of Arundel, and Bailiff of Arundel and was married firstly Thomas Fitz Alan's cousin, Blanche de Mowbray.\n\nThe following facts from the parliament site relate to this John Wiltshire: \n1. WILTSHIRE, John, of Arundel and Lyminster, Suss. \n2. \"John Wiltshire, who attested the shire returns of 1447 and was living in Arundel in the 1450s\".\n\nJohn Wiltshire received Clothall's moiety after his brother-in-law died in 1454 when it was then inherited by his wife, Isabella Clothall, in 1455. This clearly indicates that John Wiltshire died shortly after his brother-in-law in 1454.\n\nIt is this John Wiltshire b. after 1409, who married Isabella Clothall b before 1409 when her father died. She was the daughter of John Clothall (II) and Isabel (LNU) of West Grinstead, Sussex.\n\nJohn's father, Sir John Wiltshire's will, was drafted in Heylesdon on November 17, 1424, and was proved on May 25, 1428. His father wished to be buried in the priory of Lewes in Sussex by his first wife, Blanche de Mowbray. His will names his son John (GKTJ-3MH) and his second wife, Alice Heylesdon, executors.\n\nBy 1437, John Wilshire and Isabella Clothall had a daughter Joan Wiltshire (b. 1437), who married Thomas Bellingham of Lyminster. The continued pattern of inheritance of Clothall's moiety went to Thomas Bellingham.\n\nThe connection between this John Wiltshire and Isabella Clothall of Arundel and Lyminster is clear, including their daughter Jane (Joan) Wiltshire, who married Thomas Bellingham of Lyminster.  The pedigree chart of Clothall, Bellingham, Boys, and Ferris contains errors based on genealogy facts from sources and dates collected:\n\nJane is the daughter and heir of John Wiltshire and Isabella Clothall, not of \"John Wiltshire; arms in Slaugham church impaling a lion ==\". \n\nJohn Wiltshire of Arundel and Lyminster (GKTJ-3MH) is not Sir John Wiltshire of Stone (Stone Castle) near Dartford, Comptroller of Callis, and Sheriff of Kent. I have proven John Wiltshire of Stone Castle (LVX5-CDV) was born in 1434 in Essex, died in 1526 in Kent, and was only married to Margaret Graunt (MLWL-KR6) and is buried with her.\n\nSir John Wiltshire of Arundel and Lyminster and Sir John Wiltshire of Stone Castle descend from two brothers, sons of John de Wiltshire, the London grocer, spicer, and chief tenant to Richard II. Descendant paths are identified based on an exhaustive genealogical standard exhaustive search and review of hundreds of published sources.\n\nSir John Wiltshire of Arundel and Lyminster (GKTJ-3MH) was the son of Sir John Wiltshire of Arundel (GKTN-ZN3) and Alice Heylesdon (9M4T-BBS), son of John de Wiltshire (GKB8-YMW) and Joan Kelleshull Heydon (GKBJ-6B2).\n\nSir John Wiltshire of Stone Castle (G48X-6ZX) has no traceability to Isabel Clothall or her daughter Jane or properties inherited, time, or place.  This John Wiltshire married only Margaret le Grant, and he was the son of Nicholas Wiltshire (GKB6-K94) and Margaret d'Acklevit of Norway (GKB6-NRT), son of Richard Wiltshire, Esq. (GKB6-P8X) and wife unknown,  son of John de Wiltshire (GKB8-YMW) and Joan Kelleshull Heydon (GKBJ-6B2).","sourceList":[{"title":"The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1386-1421, WILTSHIRE, John, of Arundel and Lyminster, Sussex","sourceType":"DEFAULT","sourceLink":"https://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/wiltshire-john","sourceUri":"QD8C-7FR"},{"title":"London: Victoria County History, Part 2, 1953","sourceType":"DEFAULT","sourceLink":"https://buist-keatch.org/buist/goring/3658.html#1","sourceUri":"QZPK-YTB"},{"title":"The Parochial Topography of the Rape of Bramber in the Western Division of the County of Sussex, by Edmund Cartwright, M:A. F:A:S., Canon of Chichester, Rector of Earnley, Vicar of Lyminster, and Chaplain to HRH the Duke of Gloucester, VOL. II Part 2","sourceType":"DEFAULT","sourceLink":"https://books.google.com/books?id=MFoMAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA244&lpg=PA244&dq=John+Wiltshire+Isabella+Clothall&source=bl&ots=q-_U9mpyZE&sig=ACfU3U285oKoLr5XL2ORxj-fEr7SLWibmQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjf4uTGncP_AhVHg4kEHTfHBeU4HhDoAXoECAIQAw#v=onepage&q=John%20Wiltshire%20Isabella%20Clothall&f=false","sourceUri":"QZLR-GNR"}],"events":[{"name":"Birth","sources":"0","year":"1410","date":"after March 1410","place":"Hellesdon, Norfolk, England"},{"name":"Death of Parent","sources":"0","year":"1428","date":"bef